<subSubSection id="04FF6571FFCDCA0CFF37FB1BC0F9F99C" pageId="7" pageNumber="186" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="4C5A36FAFFCDCA0CFF37FB1BC311FA96" blockId="7.[140,381,1273,1300]" box="[140,381,1273,1300]" pageId="7" pageNumber="186">
<heading id="17128196FFCDCA0CFF37FB1BC311FA96" box="[140,381,1273,1300]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="7" pageNumber="186" reason="3">
<emphasis id="7E91EAE8FFCDCA0CFF37FB1BC311FA96" bold="true" box="[140,381,1273,1300]" pageId="7" pageNumber="186">
<taxonomicName id="8BE54D79FFCDCA0CFF37FB1BC295FA96" box="[140,249,1273,1300]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Cerastes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="186" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7E91EAE8FFCDCA0CFF37FB1BC295FA96" bold="true" box="[140,249,1273,1300]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="186">Cerastes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="8BE54D79FFCDCA0CFE80FB1BC311FA96" authorityName="Merrem" authorityYear="1820" box="[315,381,1273,1300]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Echis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="186" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7E91EAE8FFCDCA0CFE80FB1BC311FA96" bold="true" box="[315,381,1273,1300]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="186">Echis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4C5A36FAFFCDCA0CFF37FAD2C0F9F99C" blockId="7.[140,1108,1328,1672]" pageId="7" pageNumber="186">
These two genera have been united in a monophyletic group based on the shared character of serrated lateral scales which they use for producing a warning sound like a rattle-snake (Groombridge 1986). It is considered an adaptation to desert conditions. However, as the harmless colubrid 
<taxonomicName id="8BE54D79FFCDCA0CFDA5FA78C0E6FA36" authorityName="Wagler" authorityYear="1830" box="[542,650,1434,1460]" class="Reptilia" family="Colubridae" genus="Dasypeltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="186" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7E91EAE8FFCDCA0CFDA5FA78C0E6FA36" box="[542,650,1434,1460]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="186">Dasypeltis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and some species of African bushvipers (genus 
<taxonomicName id="8BE54D79FFCDCA0CFF64FA5FC347FA55" authorityName="Cope" authorityYear="1862" box="[223,299,1469,1495]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Atheris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="186" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7E91EAE8FFCDCA0CFF64FA5FC347FA55" box="[223,299,1469,1495]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="186">Atheris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) possess the same 
<typeStatus id="935E8858FFCDCA0CFDB8FA5CC05FFA5A" box="[515,563,1470,1496]" pageId="7" pageNumber="186">type</typeStatus>
of serrated scales, a convergent development is possible (
<bibRefCitation id="28744B0BFFCDCA0CFF4EFA02C06FFA78" author="Joger U &amp; Courage K" box="[245,515,1504,1530]" pageId="7" pageNumber="186" pagination="65 - 81" refId="ref3675" refString="Joger U, Courage K (1999) Are palaearctic &quot; rattlesnakes &quot; (Echis and Cerastes) monophyletic? - Kaupia 8: 65 - 81." type="journal article" year="1999">Joger &amp; Courage 1999</bibRefCitation>
). A new phylogenetic analysis (Pook et al., in press) confirms the monophyly of 
<taxonomicName id="8BE54D79FFCDCA0CFE72F9E1C06DF99F" authorityName="Merrem" authorityYear="1820" box="[457,513,1539,1565]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Echis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="186" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7E91EAE8FFCDCA0CFE72F9E1C06DF99F" box="[457,513,1539,1565]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="186">Echis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="8BE54D79FFCDCA0CFD82F9E6C0E2F99C" box="[569,654,1540,1566]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Cerastes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="186" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7E91EAE8FFCDCA0CFD82F9E6C0E2F99C" box="[569,654,1540,1566]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="186">Cerastes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="04FF6571FFCDCA03FF02F9C5C03DFD53" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="187" pageId="7" pageNumber="186" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="4C5A36FAFFCDCA03FF02F9C5C175FECF" blockId="7.[140,1108,1328,1672]" lastBlockId="8.[140,1108,167,1460]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="187" pageId="7" pageNumber="186">
<taxonomicName id="8BE54D79FFCDCA0CFF02F9C5C362F9C3" box="[185,270,1575,1601]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Cerastes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="186" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7E91EAE8FFCDCA0CFF02F9C5C362F9C3" box="[185,270,1575,1601]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="186">Cerastes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the Horned vipers, do not always bear horns on top of their supraorbital scales. There is a hornless species, 
<taxonomicName id="8BE54D79FFCDCA0CFDADF9A8C0DAF9E6" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[534,694,1610,1636]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Cerastes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="186" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vipera">
<emphasis id="7E91EAE8FFCDCA0CFDADF9A8C0DAF9E6" box="[534,694,1610,1636]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="186">Cerastes vipera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is found in sand dune areas in North Africa, 
<collectingCountry id="34F2766AFFCDCA0CFEF5F98CC3FDF90A" box="[334,401,1646,1672]" name="Egypt" pageId="7" pageNumber="186">Egypt</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="34F2766AFFCDCA0CFE77F98FC066F905" box="[460,522,1645,1671]" name="Israel" pageId="7" pageNumber="186">Israel</collectingCountry>
/ 
<collectingCountry id="34F2766AFFCDCA0CFDA9F98FC01BF905" box="[530,631,1645,1671]" name="Palestine" pageId="7" pageNumber="186">Palestine</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName id="8BE54D79FFCDCA0CFD3FF98CC141F905" authority="cerastes" box="[644,813,1646,1672]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Cerastes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="186" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cerastes">
<emphasis id="7E91EAE8FFCDCA0CFD3FF98CC141F905" box="[644,813,1646,1672]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="186">Cerastes cerastes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a less specialized species, maybe horned or hornless (
<figureCitation id="D4DE2A7FFFC2CA03FE78FF45C066FF43" box="[451,522,167,193]" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="9.[140,212,775,797]" captionTargetBox="[140,1108,165,755]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[140,1108,165,756]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 8. Cerastes gasperettii (horned)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3767411" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3767411/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">Figs 8</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="D4DE2A7FFFC2CA03FDA3FF45C04BFF43" box="[536,551,167,193]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="9.[140,212,1484,1506]" captionTargetBox="[140,1108,819,1464]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[140,1108,819,1465]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 9. Cerastes gasperettii (hornless)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3767413" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3767413/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">9</figureCitation>
) and occupies, in a number of subspecies, desert and semi-desert areas in North Africa and western Arabia (
<bibRefCitation id="28744B0BFFC2CA03FCA6FF28C198FF66" author="Werner YL &amp; Le Verdier A &amp; Rosenman D &amp; Sivan N" box="[797,1012,202,228]" pageId="8" pageNumber="187" pagination="90 - 100" refId="ref4417" refString="Werner YL, Le Verdier A, Rosenman D, Sivan N (1991) Systematics and zoogeography of Cerastes (Ophidia: Viperidae) in the Levant: 1. Distinguishing Arabian from African &quot; Cerastes cerastes &quot;. Th e Snake 23: 90 - 100." type="journal article" year="1991">Werner et al. 1991</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="28744B0BFFC2CA03FC44FF28C328FE85" author="Werner YL &amp; Sivan N" pageId="8" pageNumber="187" pagination="34 - 49" refId="ref4466" refString="Werner YL, Sivan N (1992) Systematics and zoogeography of Cerastes (Ophidia: Viperidae) in the Levant: 2. Taxonomy, ecology, and zoogeography. Th e Snake 24: 34 - 49." type="journal article" year="1992">Werner and Sivan 1992</bibRefCitation>
). Th e typical desert snake of most of Arabia and Khuzistan province (
<collectingCountry id="34F2766AFFC2CA03FF2FFEF2C2A9FEA8" box="[148,197,272,298]" name="Iran" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">Iran</collectingCountry>
) is 
<taxonomicName id="8BE54D79FFC2CA03FF48FEF3C169FEA8" authority="Leviton &amp; Anderson, 1967" authorityName="Leviton &amp; Anderson" authorityYear="1967" box="[243,773,272,299]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Cerastes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="8" pageNumber="187" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gasperettii">
<emphasis id="7E91EAE8FFC2CA03FF48FEF3C3D2FEA8" box="[243,446,273,299]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">Cerastes gasperettii</emphasis>
Leviton &amp; Anderson, 1967
</taxonomicName>
(Gasperetti 1980), the sister species of 
<taxonomicName id="8BE54D79FFC2CA03FF45FED6C307FECF" box="[254,363,308,334]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Cerastes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="8" pageNumber="187" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cerastes">
<emphasis id="7E91EAE8FFC2CA03FF45FED6C307FECF" box="[254,363,308,334]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">C. cerastes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but which nearly always bears horns.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4C5A36FAFFC2CA03FF02FEB5C3BBFD2C" blockId="8.[140,1108,167,1460]" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">
<taxonomicName id="8BE54D79FFC2CA03FF02FEB5C29DFEF3" authorityName="Merrem" authorityYear="1820" box="[185,241,343,369]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Echis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="8" pageNumber="187" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7E91EAE8FFC2CA03FF02FEB5C29DFEF3" box="[185,241,343,369]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">Echis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the Saw-scaled vipers, are found in a very large area from West Africa to 
<collectingCountry id="34F2766AFFC2CA03FF37FE98C2A6FE16" box="[140,202,378,404]" name="India" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">India</collectingCountry>
, including most of the Middle East countries. Th eir systematics and taxonomy have been a discussed for decades. 
<bibRefCitation id="28744B0BFFC2CA03FDAAFE7FC0A3FE3A" author="Klemmer K" box="[529,719,413,440]" pageId="8" pageNumber="187" pagination="255 - 464" refId="ref3703" refString="Klemmer K (1963) Liste der rezenten Giftschlangen. Elapidae, Hydropheidae, Viperdae und Crotalidae. p. 255 - 464 In: Die Giftschlangen der Erde. Behringwerk - Mitt., Sonderband. Marburg." type="book chapter" year="1963">Klemmer (1963)</bibRefCitation>
recognized only two species: 
<taxonomicName id="8BE54D79FFC2CA03FBA0FE7FC283FE58" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Echis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="8" pageNumber="187" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carinatus">
<emphasis id="7E91EAE8FFC2CA03FBA0FE7FC283FE58" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">Echis carinatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in most of the range and 
<taxonomicName id="8BE54D79FFC2CA03FDAFFE23C1F4FE58" authority="in Arabia. Joger (1984" authorityName="in Arabia. Joger" authorityYear="1984" box="[532,920,448,475]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Echis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="8" pageNumber="187" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="coloratus">
<emphasis id="7E91EAE8FFC2CA03FDAFFE23C0FEFE58" box="[532,658,448,474]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">E. coloratus</emphasis>
in Arabia. 
<bibRefCitation id="28744B0BFFC2CA03FCABFE23C1F4FE58" author="Joger U" box="[784,920,448,475]" pageId="8" pageNumber="187" pagination="1 - 115" refId="ref3529" refString="Joger U (1984) Th e Venomous Snakes of the Near and Middle East. Beihefte zum Tubinger Atlas des Vorderen Orients, Reihe A, Nr. 12: 1 - 115." type="journal article" year="1984">Joger (1984</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="28744B0BFFC2CA03FC1FFE22C18CFE58" author="Joger U" box="[932,992,448,474]" pageId="8" pageNumber="187" pagination="257 - 271" refId="ref3564" refString="Joger U (1987) An interpretation of reptile zoogeography in Arabia, with special reference to Arabian herpetofaunal relationships with Africa. In: Kinzelbach R, Krupp F, Schneider W (Eds) Proceedings of the Symposium on the Fauna and Zoogeography of the Middle East, Mainz 1985 (Tubinger Atlas des Vorderen Orients): 257 - 271" type="journal article" year="1987">1987</bibRefCitation>
) added 
<taxonomicName id="8BE54D79FFC2CA03FB80FE23C365FE7F" baseAuthorityName="Geoffroy Saint-hilaire" baseAuthorityYear="1827" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Echis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="8" pageNumber="187" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pyramidum">
<emphasis id="7E91EAE8FFC2CA03FB80FE23C365FE7F" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">E. pyramidum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for southwestern Arabia. 
<bibRefCitation id="28744B0BFFC2CA03FD8AFE01C0B2FE7C" author="Cherlin V" box="[561,734,483,510]" pageId="8" pageNumber="187" pagination="193 - 223" refId="ref3239" refString="Cherlin V (1990) Taxonomic revision of the snake genus Echis. II. An analysis of taxonomy and description of new forms. In: Borkin L. J. (Ed) Reptiles of mountain and arid territories: systematics and distribution. Proc. Zool. Inst. USSR Acad. Sci. 207: 193 - 223 (in Russian, with English summary)." type="journal article" year="1990">Cherlin (1990)</bibRefCitation>
described a number of new species and subspecies and increased the total number of 
<taxonomicName id="8BE54D79FFC2CA03FD5CFDE5C173FDA3" authorityName="Merrem" authorityYear="1820" box="[743,799,519,545]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Echis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="8" pageNumber="187" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7E91EAE8FFC2CA03FD5CFDE5C173FDA3" box="[743,799,519,545]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">Echis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species significantly. A new species within the 
<taxonomicName id="8BE54D79FFC2CA03FEE0FDC9C3B4FDC6" authorityName="in Arabia. Joger" authorityYear="1984" box="[347,472,554,580]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Echis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="8" pageNumber="187" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="coloratus">
<emphasis id="7E91EAE8FFC2CA03FEE0FDC9C3B4FDC6" box="[347,472,554,580]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">E. coloratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group was described by 
<bibRefCitation id="28744B0BFFC2CA03FD50FDC8C1C7FDC6" author="Babocsay G" box="[747,939,554,580]" pageId="8" pageNumber="187" pagination="503 - 514" refId="ref3146" refString="Babocsay G (2004) A new species of the Echis coloratus complex (Ophidia: Viperidae) from Oman, Eastern Arabia. Systematics Biodiversity 1: 503 - 514." type="journal article" year="2004">Babocsay (2004)</bibRefCitation>
. Pook et al. (in press), using molecular genetic methods, have now clarified the complicated situation. On the basis of their results and additional data, we recognize the following six species in the Near and Middle East:
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4C5A36FAFFC2CA03FF02FD55C03DFD53" blockId="8.[140,1108,167,1460]" box="[185,593,695,721]" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">
<taxonomicName id="8BE54D79FFC2CA03FF02FD55C337FD52" box="[185,347,695,721]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Echis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="8" pageNumber="187" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carinatus">
<emphasis id="7E91EAE8FFC2CA03FF02FD55C337FD52" box="[185,347,695,721]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="187">Echis carinatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (Asian group):
</paragraph>
